s, is to understand how the enzyme telomerase, that adds telomeric DNA to the tips of chromosomes, functions. Since the telomerase is active in 90% of human tumours, this is a structural project of both medical and biological importance.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>My research focuses on two different aspects of chromosome structure and function. Our goals are to understand how the structure of chromatin is involved in transcriptional regulation, and how the telomerase enzyme replenishes the tips of chromosomes.|During the last 10 years chromatin has been brought to the forefront of biology. The discovery of chromatin remodelling complexes and enzymes that modify histone proteins post-transcriptionally has established the fundamental role of chromatin structure in regulating DNA-based nuclear processes such as transcription and replication. Since condensed chromatin occludes the majority of proteins whose function depends on accessing DNA, it is thought that the folding and unfolding of chromatin is central to the regulation of these processes. An understanding of the mechanism of folding and unfolding and the actual role of histone modifications will require structural information. Through structural studies initiated at the LMB 25 years ago, we now have a high resolution view of the nucleosome core particle, in which 147bp of DNA are wrapped into 1.7 turns of a left-handed superhelix around the histone octamer (2 copies each of histones H2A, H2B, H3 and H4). One copy of the fifth histone, the linker histone H1/H5 organizes an additional 20bp of DNA and completes the nucleosome. In the next level of folding, the 10nm nucleosome array folds into a fibre with a 30nm diameter.|The tips of linear eukaryotic chromosomes are capped by multi protein-DNA complexes called telomeres. They prevent chromosome ends from being recognized and processed as sites of DNA damage, and loss of capping function results in genetic instability and loss of cellular viability. Telomeric DNA consists of conserved, short sequence repeats that are added by the enzyme telomerase, a large ribonucleoprotein complex consisting of the catalytic subunit with reverse transcriptase activity and an RNA subunit that encodes the template for the telomeric DNA synthesis. This enzyme is a particularly important target for structural analysis, since it is upregulated in 90% of human cancers.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2015-07-02</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>1992-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>3564455</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>Witten/Herdecke University (UWH)</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>Germany, Federal Republic of</gtr:country><gtr:department>The Institute of Cell Biology (ICB)</gtr:department><gtr:description>G-quadruplexes and telomerase recruitment</gtr:description><gtr:id>1D7F9FAA-C429-4BD9-94C6-5D00823BFCB5</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Telomerase recruitment by the telomere end binding protein-beta facilitates G-quadruplex DNA unfolding in ciliates Paeschke K, Juranek S, Simonsson T, Hempel A, Rhodes D and Lipps HJ. (joint corresponding author) (2008) Nat. Struct. Mol. Biol. 15(6): 598-604 Cell cycle-dependent regulation of telomere tethering in the nucleus Paeschke K, Juranek S, Rhodes D and Lipps HJ. (joint corresponding author) (2008) Chromosome Res. 16(5): 721-8 G-quadruplex structures: in vivo evidence and function. Lipps HJ, Rhodes D. (2009) Trends Cell Biol. 19: 414-422</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>B4420175E4F-1</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partnerContribution>Hans Lipps brought me into this important area of biology because he needed biochemical expertise.</gtr:partnerContribution><gtr:piCo